Detailed requirements

1. Source restriction and ingestion
- Only ingest from `https://www.ebanglalibrary.com/`.
- Accept these submission inputs through UI and/or API:
  - direct `ebanglalibrary.com` book URLs
  - titles or book names that must be resolved to a valid `ebanglalibrary.com` URL
- Support bulk submission through:
  - pasted multiline URLs
  - pasted multiline titles
  - CSV upload
- Build a title-to-URL resolution flow specific to `ebanglalibrary.com`.
- Reuse the repo's existing normalization and fuzzy-comparison ideas where helpful.
- Normalize Bengali and English punctuation and spacing during matching.
- Crawl or index only the `ebanglalibrary` catalog/discovery surface needed for resolution.
- Store:
  - the original submitted input
  - the resolved URL, if any
  - resolution status
  - confidence
  - timestamps
  - submitter identity
  - audit trail
- When there is no confident exact match, show up to 3 close candidates with enough context for a human to choose.
- Do not auto-select a fuzzy match without explicit confirmation.
- If a user does not confirm a fuzzy match, keep the submission pending review rather than guessing.
- Reject or flag anything that resolves outside `ebanglalibrary.com`.

2. Metadata extraction and normalization
- Reuse and improve the current scraper logic for:
  - book title
  - author/writer
  - translator
  - editor
  - category/type/genre
  - series
  - cover image
  - book info/front matter
  - dedication
  - TOC
  - lesson/topic content
- Preserve raw scraped values for provenance and debugging.
- Introduce a normalization layer that converts current flat scraper output into canonical structured records.
- When scraped metadata contains comma-separated lists for contributors, series, or categories/types:
  - keep the raw string for provenance
  - split it into separate normalized records for the canonical model
- Contributor roles must be explicit and queryable.
- Extracted metadata must remain editable and reviewable by authorized users.
- Keep the extraction pipeline deterministic first. Future AI enrichment must be additive, not required.

3. Data model and persistence
- Use a relational schema with at least these concepts:
  - books
  - book submissions
  - title resolution attempts
  - match candidates
  - source URLs
  - contributors/people
  - contributor roles
  - book contributors
  - series
  - book-series relationships
  - categories/types
  - book-category/type relationships
  - generated assets
  - processing jobs and logs
  - users
  - role bundles or permission grants
  - per-book access rules
  - audit logs
  - metadata review states
  - metadata version history
  - duplicate review/merge records
  - preview/read access sessions or tokens
  - reading progress or reading sessions if reader state is supported
  - bookmarks if reader state is supported
- Support many-to-many relationships where the data naturally requires them.
- Keep raw provenance alongside canonical normalized relationships.
- Support states such as:
  - draft
  - processing
  - needs review
  - ready
  - published
  - archived
  - soft deleted

4. Background processing
- Move scraping and generation work into background jobs.
- Track states such as:
  - queued
  - processing
  - succeeded
  - failed
- Preserve failure details, retry history, and links to the related submission/book.
- Provide a queue/process view for admins or reviewers.
- Make reprocessing safe and repeatable without manual filesystem cleanup.

5. Duplicate handling and review
- Detect duplicates using:
  - exact source URL matching
  - normalized metadata comparison where appropriate
- Provide reviewable flows for:
  - duplicate detection
  - duplicate review
  - duplicate merge/linking
  - title-resolution review
- Never silently discard a submission just because the book already exists.
- Preserve the submission record and link it to the existing book where appropriate.

6. Search, filtering, and discovery
- Support search/filtering for:
  - book title
  - submitted title/query
  - author/contributor
  - category/type
  - series
  - creation date
  - processing status
  - submission status
  - review status
- Searches over authors, series, and categories/types must operate on normalized related records, not only raw comma-joined strings.
- Provide usable sorting and saved filters where reasonable.
- Use slug-based URLs where appropriate.
- Make the library feel like a real catalog, not a table dump.

7. Authentication and authorization
- Use email + password authentication.
- Support password reset by email.
- Support TOTP-based 2FA.
- Seed or initialize `rsalehin24@gmail.com` as the super admin account without hardcoding unsafe credentials.
- Support self-service signup if needed for the broad submission model.
- Prefer secure HttpOnly session-cookie auth with CSRF protection unless another approach is clearly justified.
- If frontend and backend live on different origins/subdomains, configure CSRF, CORS, and trusted origins safely and explicitly.
- The frontend must be able to fetch:
  - current user
  - session/auth state
  - 2FA state
  - effective permission scopes/capabilities
- Handle `401` and `403` cleanly in the frontend.
- Backend authorization is mandatory for:
  - protected APIs
  - file downloads
  - reader launch flows
  - metadata editing
  - processing management
  - access management
- Frontend route guards are helpful for UX, but never sufficient for security.
- Model permissions so a user can hold multiple grants at once.
- Support action-level permissions such as:
  - submit/create
  - preview/read once
  - durable read/reopen
  - download
  - edit metadata
  - manage processing
  - manage access
  - admin/full control

8. Public vs protected behavior
- Broad submission should be supported, but durable read/download access must remain policy-driven.
- The submitter of a book is not automatically entitled to permanent read/download access.
- A newly generated book may support a short-lived preview or result-session read flow where appropriate.
- Repeated reading, reopening, and downloading must require proper authorization.
- Public-facing submission endpoints still need validation, abuse protection, rate limiting, and audit logging.

9. EPUB output, download, and reader integration
- Continue generating EPUB files from the refactored services.
- Preserve or improve the current HTML output path too.
- After successful generation, present clear actions such as:
  - `Download`
  - `Download and View`
- For multiple generated books, support bulk actions.
- Protect download and reader-launch flows with backend validation and short-lived signed access or an equivalent secure mechanism.
- Do not rely only on client-side checks.
- Integrate reader launch with `https://ereader.rsalehin24.me/`.
- If authorized users open multiple books for reading as part of a direct user action, support separate tabs/windows where appropriate.
- Persist reading state if feasible:
  - progress
  - last opened location
  - bookmarks

10. UI/UX expectations
- Build a responsive React UI that feels like a premium digital library/catalog product.
- Do not make it look like a generic admin dashboard or a generic e-reader clone.
- Use a clear visual direction:
  - cover-forward presentation
  - refined typography
  - calm, library-appropriate palette
  - polished loading, empty, success, and error states
  - strong spacing and hierarchy
- Build reusable design tokens/components so the UI stays coherent.
- Core product surfaces should include:
  - library home
  - submission/import flow
  - title-resolution disambiguation flow
  - processing/results view
  - book detail page
  - review/metadata correction flows
  - user/access management screens
- After successful creation of one or many books, show a polished completion state with per-book and bulk actions.
- Make the distinction between temporary preview access and durable authorized access obvious in the UI.
- Keep the UI accessible:
  - keyboard navigation
  - visible focus states
  - reasonable contrast
  - reduced-motion support
  - mobile-friendly touch targets

11. Operations and maintainability
- Replace the root `.gitignore` with a real one for Python, Django, React/Node, Docker, env files, logs, caches, build artifacts, generated assets, editor noise, OS noise, and local venvs.
- Use environment variables for secrets and environment-specific config.
- Keep storage abstract enough that local storage works now and S3/object storage can be added later.
- Keep file naming and path handling safe.
- Add validation, structured logging, audit logging, and error handling throughout.
- Protect public-facing or submission-heavy flows from abuse.
- Create a README if missing and document:
  - architecture
  - setup
  - env vars
  - configuration migration from the old script/config flow
  - Docker usage
  - local development workflow
  - frontend deployment workflow
  - backend deployment workflow
  - migrations
  - running backend/frontend
  - running workers
  - seeding the admin account
  - known blockers and assumptions
- Keep a progress log or implementation notes so interrupted work can be resumed cleanly.

12. Testing expectations
- Add tests for the most important flows, especially:
  - auth and 2FA
  - authorization and protected file access
  - submission validation
  - title resolution/disambiguation
  - duplicate handling
  - job processing state transitions
  - metadata normalization and persistence
  - scraper/service behavior that is practical to test deterministically
- Prefer focused service/model/API tests over only shallow UI smoke tests.
- Do not claim completion without running the most relevant verification commands for the work you changed.

